  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Culture of peace and institutionality for the fulfillment of human rights in El Salvador</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Currently, El Salvador faces human rights violations of its population in different aspects. According to the 2018 Human Rights Report published by the UCA Institute of Human Rights (IDHUCA), for that year they registered:
- Alarming violations of the right to life, reflected in the 3,341 homicides and the homicide rate of 53.98 per 100,000 people.
- Epidemic levels of femicides.
- Lack of a transitional justice law.
- Forced displacement as a result of high levels of insecurity.
- The judicial arbitrariness established in official proceedings.
- Deficiency in environmental regulation, reflected in the lack of guarantees for the enjoyment of the right to water and other essential resources for life.

In that sense, from a humanistic approach inspired in the integral ecology, it is necessary to generate the conditions that guarantee the respect of the human rights of the Salvadoran population. For this, the UCA intends to intervene through two dimensions: collaborate in the construction of a culture of peace and contribute to the strengthening of public institutions.

During the pandemic (2020 and 2021) the political conflicts have been linked to the authoritarian measures implemented by the new Government. The Civil Society Sector and independent media are under permanent stigmatisation such as the international cooperation.</narrative>
  </description>
